<br>
I am 100% against the code.  I would even go as far as to say, my purchase of SOL is in question.  I LOVE EverQuest, but this code disrupts everything I have worked for in the past 2+ years.  It is a step backwards and causes many more problems than it solves.<br>
<br>
One of my most anticipated things about SOL is the addition of focus items.  I can only imagine that the vast majority of these new weapons and gear will be on greens.  To be forced into buying these upgrades via the Loot Code, is unforgivable.  The majority of players are being punished by the actions of a small section of the player populace that camp and sell.  That's what this code is after all.....a punishment.  Well, I am upset for being pusnished for something I didn't do.  I do not want to build another character for the sole purpose of gaining a lvl 36 focus item for my level 48 druid as some people have suggested.  I want to walk in, cast 4 spells, get my item, and be done with it.  It should be that way because that is something I have worked for.  If the MoB were camped by other people, I would go elsewhere, just like I do now.  <br>
<br>
What's to stop the TRUE greif players and jerks in EQ from using this code to piss people off?  I lvl 60 jerk can still PK a rare MoB and prevent the &quot;proper leveled character&quot; from obtaining the item.  This code does nothing but cause problems for the good players, and gives more loopholes for the bad ones.<br>
<br>
In reguards to finding the &quot;proper&quot; place to hunt....I couldn't agree more!  Imagine if the Tower of Frozen Shadow had the TLC code.  Who would want to spend 8+ hours trying to figure out the key spawns and what-not, only to get to the top floor and find....GREENS!  All that work for what?  Absolutely nothing, because you didn't know the highest level would be green.  A group of players would walk out with a wasted day and not a piece of loot to show for thier troubles.  BTW, that lower level loot is what alot of players make plat from to buy higher level gear.  The whole argument that high level players can and should be reduced to buying is completely screwed by the fact that our most common form of income IS LOWER LEVEL LOOT.  When SOL is released, the items from the new expansion will be the most sought after loot in the game.  Prices will skyrocket, then level off after about a month or so.  During that time, the majority of the itmes and money will be unavailable to the high level players.  I am paying the same amount as a low level player to purchase the expansion, as well as play on a month to month basis.  I feel like this would be taking away a great deal from my personal playing experiance.  I don't have a lowbie twink, nor do I desire one at this stage in the game.<br>
<br>
I do realize what VI is trying to accomplish, but this just isn't a solution in my eyes.  As a matter of fact, I really don't see high levels in lowbie zones as a large enough problem to warrent all the trouble of extra coding and what-not.  I sincerely hope they reconsider this approach.<br>
